SIMPLE: nip
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Nip
<hw>Nip</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LG. & D.
<ets>nippen</ets> to sip; akin to Dan. <ets>nippe</ets>, G.
<ets>nippen</ets>.]</ety> <def>A sip or small draught; esp., a draught
of intoxicating liquor; a dram.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Nip</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Nip
<hw>Nip</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Nipped</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>, less properly <conjf>Nipt</conjf>;
<pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Nipping</conjf>
<pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>nipen</ets>; cf. D.
<ets>niipen</ets> to pinch, also <ets>knippen</ets> to nip, clip, pinch,
snap, <ets>knijpen</ets> to pinch, LG. <ets>knipen</ets>, G.
<ets>kneipen</ets>, <ets>kneifen</ets>, to pinch, cut off, nip, Lith.
<ets>knebti</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To catch and inclose or
compress tightly between two surfaces, or points which are brought
together or closed; to pinch; to close in upon.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>May this hard earth cleave to the Nadir hell,⟦br⟧
Down, down, and close again, and <qex>nip</qex> me flat,⟦br⟧
If I be such a traitress.</q> <rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To remove by pinching, biting, or cutting with two
meeting edges of anything; to clip.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The small shoots . . . must be <qex>nipped</qex> off.</q>
<rj><qau>Mortimer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Hence: To blast, as by frost; to check the growth or
vigor of; to destroy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To vex or pain, as by nipping; hence, to
taunt.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And sharp remorse his heart did prick and <qex>nip</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To nip in the bud</b></col>, <cd>to cut off at the very
commencement of growth; to kill in the incipient stage.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Nip</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Nip
<hw>Nip</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A seizing or closing in
upon; a pinching; <as>as, in the northern seas, the <ex>nip</ex> of
masses of ice</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A pinch with the nails or teeth.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A small cut, or a cutting off the end.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A blast; a killing of the ends of plants by
frost.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A biting sarcasm; a taunt.</def>
<rj><au>Latimer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A short turn in a rope.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Nip and tuck</b></col>, <cd>a phrase signifying equality
in a contest; <as>as, it was <ex>nip and tuck</ex> right to the last
minute of play</as>.</cd> <mark>[Low, U.S.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Nipa</ent>⟦br⟧
